WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:02.500
Helo, nic Crane ydw i.

00:00:02.500 --> 00:00:05.500
Rydw i'n ymgynghoriadwr arbenigol ac adnoddwr ffyrdd ag awgrymu.

00:00:05.500 --> 00:00:09.500
Heddiw rydw i'n siarad â chi am Hacking Productivity gyda LLMs

00:00:09.500 --> 00:00:12.500
ac mae rhai brofiadau wedi'u gwneud dros y 18 mlynedd diwethaf.

00:00:12.500 --> 00:00:15.500
Fodd bynnag, roeddwn i'n meddwl yn ddiweddar

00:00:15.500 --> 00:00:18.500
am swydd rydw i'n ei wneud yn ystod fy nghyfnod.

00:00:18.500 --> 00:00:21.000
Roeddwn i'n gweithio ar y prosiect, ac fel rhan o'r prosiect,

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:25.500
roedd gen i'r swydd diwethaf o adnoddau database yn fform CSV,

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:27.500
ac roeddwn i'n ei ddatblygu i Excel,

00:00:27.500 --> 00:00:30.500
ac roeddwn i'n ymwneud â ffyrdd a ffiltrau gwahanol,

00:00:30.500 --> 00:00:33.500
ac roeddwn i'n eu cael yn unig yn iawn, ac roeddwn i'n ei rhoi i'r cymdeithaswyr.

00:00:33.500 --> 00:00:38.500
Roedd y gwaith ei hun yn anodd, ac roedd hi'n ddiddorol iawn.

00:00:38.500 --> 00:00:41.000
Roedd hi'n gweithgaredd gwirioneddol iawn,

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:44.000
ac os oedd pethau'n mynd yn iawn, roeddwn i'n rhaid i mi ddechrau o'r dechrau eto.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:49.000
Roedd hi'n mynd i'n rhaid i mi fod yn risg iawn o sefydliad yw ILD,

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:52.500
Imminent Laptop Defenestration.

00:00:52.500 --> 00:00:55.000
Ond, yn hytrach na rhannu fy mhysyn a mynd i'r ffyrdd,

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:58.500
rydw i'n dechrau cyrraedd ymwneud â pheth mwy o ddefnyddiad gwirioneddol.

00:00:58.500 --> 00:01:00.000
Roeddwn i'n creu gweithgaredd gwirioneddol,

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:02.500
ac roedd y gweithgaredd gwirioneddol yn cysylltu â'r ddatabase.

00:01:02.500 --> 00:01:05.500
Gall y defnyddwyr ddefnyddio'r ffiltrau a'r pethau sydd eu hangen arnyn nhw eu hunain,

00:01:05.500 --> 00:01:09.000
ac roeddwn i ddim yn rhaid i mi wneud y gwaith anodd hwn bob dydd.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:12.000
Felly roeddwn i'n hapus, roeddwn i'n gallu sefydlu ar bethau mwy ddiddorol,

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:13.000
ac roedden nhw'n hapus.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:16.500
Nid oedden nhw'n cael ymddangos arnaf i mi ar y pwynt honno.

00:01:16.500 --> 00:01:17.500
Ac, mewn gwirionedd,

00:01:17.500 --> 00:01:22.000
y peth gyda chreu gweithgareddau a phethau i gynyddu'r pethau,

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:23.500
mae bob amser yn ymwneud â'r risg,

00:01:23.500 --> 00:01:25.000
mae'r cyflwyniad rydych chi'n ei ddod o hyd yn oed,

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:26.500
a'r amser rydych chi'n ei ddod o hyd i'w rhoi,

00:01:26.500 --> 00:01:28.000
yn gallu cymryd llawer o amser

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:31.500
y byddai'r tasg sylfaenol yn y lle cyntaf ei hun.

00:01:31.500 --> 00:01:32.500
Ac rwy'n credu, mewn gwirionedd,

00:01:32.500 --> 00:01:34.000
mae hynny'n rhywbeth y bydd llawer ohonoch ni'n meddwl amdano

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:37.000
ar hyn o bryd o ran AI.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:39.000
Ac felly,

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:41.500
fel y sgrifennodd Cat Hicks yn ei gynhyrchiad y diwrnod diwethaf,

00:01:41.500 --> 00:01:43.000
nid yw'r unig beth y gallai'r tŷau hyn ei wneud,

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:46.000
ond mewn gwirionedd, ein profiad o gysylltu â nhw.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:48.500
Ac mae hynny'n rhywbeth sydd wedi ymddangos iawn gyda fi.

00:01:48.500 --> 00:01:49.500
Dw i wedi treulio llawer o amser,

00:01:49.500 --> 00:01:51.500
dros y 18 mlynedd diwethaf,

00:01:51.500 --> 00:01:53.000
yn ymwneud â llyfrgellau LLM,

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:56.000
ac yn ceisio cynyddu gweithredu mewn fforddau gwahanol.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:57.500
Mewn gwirionedd, mae hynny'n helpu iawn,

00:01:57.500 --> 00:01:59.500
ac mewn gwirionedd, rydw i wedi gysylltu â llyfrgellau cyfan

00:01:59.500 --> 00:02:02.000
i rhywbeth sydd ddim wedi gweithio.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:03.500
Felly, dydw i'n mynd i siarad â chi

00:02:03.500 --> 00:02:05.500
am fy mhrofiad o hynny,

00:02:05.500 --> 00:02:07.000
ac mae tri cwestiynau

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:08.500
rydw i bob amser yn ymddangos ar hyn o bryd

00:02:08.500 --> 00:02:12.500
pan rydw i'n penderfynu a ydw i'n defnyddio llyfrgell LLM mewn gwasanaeth neu ddim.

00:02:12.500 --> 00:02:14.500
Felly, y cwestiwn cyntaf yw,

00:02:14.500 --> 00:02:17.500
pa mor anodd y bydd y gwasanaeth?

00:02:17.500 --> 00:02:18.500
Rydw i'n mynd i ddangos hyn

00:02:18.500 --> 00:02:20.500
trwy siarad am rhaglen R

00:02:20.500 --> 00:02:22.500
rydw i wedi bod yn gweithio arnyn nhw'n ddiweddar.

00:02:22.500 --> 00:02:24.500
Felly, mae'r rhaglen ei hun

00:02:24.500 --> 00:02:27.000
yn ei enw Daisy UI Widget.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:29.000
Mae'n rhaglen HTML widgets,

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:30.500
ac mae hynny'n golygu ei fod yn defnyddio

00:02:30.500 --> 00:02:33.500
rhaglen HTML, JavaScript, CSS a R,

00:02:33.500 --> 00:02:35.500
ac mae'r defnyddwyr yn gweithio gyda'r rhaglen,

00:02:35.500 --> 00:02:37.500
mewn gwirionedd yn R.

00:02:37.500 --> 00:02:39.500
I weithio gyda'r rhaglen,

00:02:39.500 --> 00:02:41.500
bydd y defnyddwr yn creu ffram ddata

00:02:41.500 --> 00:02:43.500
gyda dyfodol a sylwadau.

00:02:43.500 --> 00:02:45.500
Byddent yn ei enw Daisy Function Timeline,

00:02:45.500 --> 00:02:46.500
ac byddent yn cael ein timeline,

00:02:46.500 --> 00:02:48.500
fel yr un ar y dref yma.

00:02:48.500 --> 00:02:50.500
Felly, rydw i'n penderfynu,

00:02:50.500 --> 00:02:51.500
pan oeddwn yn dechrau'r prosiect hon,

00:02:51.500 --> 00:02:52.500
i weld a allwn ei wneud

00:02:52.500 --> 00:02:54.500
o'r blaen gyda llyfrgell LLM.

00:02:54.500 --> 00:02:56.500
Felly, rydw i'n defnyddio copilot GitHub,

00:02:56.500 --> 00:02:59.500
ond rydw i'n dod ac wnaethu pompio neu gweithio i rhoi codi.

00:02:59.500 --> 00:03:02.500
Felly, sut a oedd y prosium yn mynd?

00:03:02.500 --> 00:03:03.500
Mae'n dweud, ymterwyl!

00:03:03.500 --> 00:03:05.500
Na, nid gwyddon ni'r rhan honno,

00:03:05.500 --> 00:03:07.500
ond dywodd rhywbeth y byddai arall yn rhaglen R.

00:03:07.500 --> 00:03:08.500
Ond, pan fe wnaethon ni wneud y ffinctrion,

00:03:08.500 --> 00:03:10.500
mae'n debyg o'i radd,

00:03:10.500 --> 00:03:12.500
roedd yn teimlo iddo y data Jeavoscript a Cyflog CSS

00:03:12.500 --> 00:03:14.500
oedd ar gyd gydol y chwaraeth mae o nich du.

00:03:14.500 --> 00:03:16.500
Roedd propfon hyn yn braiu cadarn.

00:03:16.500 --> 00:03:17.500
Concludais,

00:03:18.500 --> 00:03:21.500
Nid oeddwn i'n gwybod lle i ddechrau gwneud hynny.

00:03:21.500 --> 00:03:23.500
Roeddwn i'n dweud,

00:03:23.500 --> 00:03:26.500
os yw'r gwaith yn eithaf anodd neu anhygoel,

00:03:26.500 --> 00:03:28.500
gallwch chi ddechrau a chynhyrchu ychydig o codi,

00:03:28.500 --> 00:03:30.500
ond pan fyddwn ni'n dod i'r pwynt hwn

00:03:30.500 --> 00:03:32.500
o ddod i'r cwestiwn cyflym,

00:03:32.500 --> 00:03:34.500
bydd pethau'n gweithio'n iawn yno.

00:03:34.500 --> 00:03:36.500
Felly, ar hyn o bryd,

00:03:36.500 --> 00:03:38.500
roedd gen i ychydig o'r rhaglen,

00:03:38.500 --> 00:03:40.500
ond, yn hytrach, roedd fy ffrind i'w helpu

00:03:40.500 --> 00:03:42.500
i'w datblygu,

00:03:43.500 --> 00:03:45.500
ac roeddwn i eisiau gweld

00:03:45.500 --> 00:03:47.500
os oedd LLMs'n gallu helpu.

00:03:47.500 --> 00:03:49.500
Felly, roeddwn i'n ddechrau gwneud ymlaen

00:03:49.500 --> 00:03:51.500
ar y tasg ddau.

00:03:51.500 --> 00:03:53.500
Felly, roedd y slot AI

00:03:53.500 --> 00:03:55.500
rydw i wedi'i ddod allan o'r copilot GitHub

00:03:55.500 --> 00:03:57.500
wedi dod â'r ffordd hwn

00:03:57.500 --> 00:03:59.500
o weithio gyda'r rhaglen,

00:03:59.500 --> 00:04:01.500
lle roedd y rhaglen FunctionDaisy

00:04:01.500 --> 00:04:03.500
yn cymryd llys o llys yn ei chynhyrchu.

00:04:03.500 --> 00:04:05.500
Ond mewn gwirionedd,

00:04:05.500 --> 00:04:07.500
ar gyfer pethau fel hyn,

00:04:07.500 --> 00:04:09.500
mae'n fwy cyffredinol

00:04:09.500 --> 00:04:11.500
i gael rhaglen data fel cynhyrchu.

00:04:11.500 --> 00:04:13.500
Felly, yr hyn rydw i'n ei wneud yma

00:04:13.500 --> 00:04:15.500
oedd newid y rhaglen o llys o llys i'r rhaglen data.

00:04:15.500 --> 00:04:17.500
Felly, roedd e'n teimlo fel tasg.

00:04:17.500 --> 00:04:19.500
Roeddwn i'n gallu deall sut i'w wneud fy hun.

00:04:19.500 --> 00:04:21.500
Nid oedd e'n cymryd llawer o amser,

00:04:21.500 --> 00:04:23.500
ond roeddwn i eisiau gweld beth a oedd yn digwydd

00:04:23.500 --> 00:04:25.500
os oedd gen i LLM i'w wneud.

00:04:25.500 --> 00:04:27.500
Iawn, felly, sut mae'r rhaglen hon yn mynd?

00:04:27.500 --> 00:04:29.500
Mae'n bwysig iawn.

00:04:29.500 --> 00:04:31.500
Felly, roeddwn i'n digwydd

00:04:31.500 --> 00:04:33.500
gyda'r codd anhygoel hwn

00:04:33.500 --> 00:04:35.500
sydd wedi bod yn llwyr o llwybrau

00:04:35.500 --> 00:04:37.500
rydw i erioed ddim wedi gweld.

00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:39.500
Roedd y codd yn ymwneud â llawer o testau.

00:04:39.500 --> 00:04:41.500
Ar gyfer y rhan fach o codd,

00:04:41.500 --> 00:04:43.500
rydw i erioed ddim wedi gweld llawer o testau yn ymwneud â hyn.

00:04:43.500 --> 00:04:45.500
Roedd y codd yn teimlo'n fwysig iawn

00:04:45.500 --> 00:04:47.500
i gael mynd i gysylltu â'i gilydd.

00:04:47.500 --> 00:04:49.500
Roedd y codd yn ymwneud â'r codd yn ddiddorol hefyd.

00:04:49.500 --> 00:04:51.500
Felly, roedd y codd yn gweithio

00:04:51.500 --> 00:04:53.500
ac roedd yn ymwneud â'r hyn sy'n ei ddweud.

00:04:53.500 --> 00:04:55.500
Ond, pan roeddwn i'n mynd trwy'r codd,

00:04:55.500 --> 00:04:57.500
roedd llawer i fynd ag e.

00:04:57.500 --> 00:04:59.500
Rwy'n teimlo bod cadarnhau codd yn

00:04:59.500 --> 00:05:01.500
mwy o wrsg cymdeithasol.

00:05:01.500 --> 00:05:03.500
Gall fod yn mwynhau i gysylltu â phobl.

00:05:03.500 --> 00:05:05.500
Ond rydw i'n dod yn ôl i gofyn,

00:05:05.500 --> 00:05:07.500
a oedd y codd i'w defnyddio'n ymwneud â'r cyfrif?

00:05:07.500 --> 00:05:09.500
a oedd y model arall a'i ddefnyddio?

00:05:09.500 --> 00:05:11.500
a oedd y data a ddifrifoeddodd arno?

00:05:11.500 --> 00:05:13.500
A oedd y codd hwnna'n dda iawn?

00:05:13.500 --> 00:05:15.500
Ac, yn siŵr, ro'n i'n gwerthfawr

00:05:15.500 --> 00:05:17.500
i fynd â'r cwestiynau hyn, ond yn ddifrifol

00:05:47.500 --> 00:05:49.500
i ddefnyddio'r cyfrif.

00:05:49.500 --> 00:05:51.500
Felly, os yw'n ei ddefnyddio'n ymwneud â'r cyfrif,

00:05:51.500 --> 00:05:53.500
yn y cyfrif hon, gallwn gael rhywun yn clicio ar gyfer

00:05:53.500 --> 00:05:55.500
unrhyw beth yn y cyfrifiad,

00:05:55.500 --> 00:05:57.500
ac yna gwerthfawr yn cyfrifio'r cyfrif

00:05:57.500 --> 00:05:59.500
fel y gallwn, efallai, ddangos rhai teistiau

00:05:59.500 --> 00:06:01.500
sy'n ymwneud â'r cyfrif.

00:06:01.500 --> 00:06:03.500
Ac roeddwn i eisiau gweld a allwn i'w ddefnyddio hyn.

00:06:03.500 --> 00:06:05.500
Felly, eto, roeddwn i'n dod â'r codd.

00:06:05.500 --> 00:06:07.500
Roeddwn i'n dod â'r codd.

00:06:07.500 --> 00:06:09.500
Roeddwn i'n dod â'r codd.

00:06:39.500 --> 00:06:41.500
Roeddwn i'n dod â'r codd.

00:06:41.500 --> 00:06:43.500
Felly, gallwn ei ddefnyddio fel hyn.

00:06:43.500 --> 00:06:45.500
Felly, ie, os yw'r tasg eithaf hawdd,

00:06:45.500 --> 00:06:47.500
mae'n teimlo fel,

00:06:47.500 --> 00:06:49.500
ddangos mwy o amser,

00:06:49.500 --> 00:06:51.500
os yw'r tasg eithaf anodd,

00:06:51.500 --> 00:06:53.500
dwi ddim yn gallu ymwneud â'r codd,

00:06:53.500 --> 00:06:55.500
ond mewn gwirionedd, os yw'n fwy anodd,

00:06:55.500 --> 00:06:57.500
mae hynny'n lle ddiddorol.

00:06:57.500 --> 00:06:59.500
Ac mewn gwirionedd, pan ddewisais hyn fel hyn,

00:06:59.500 --> 00:07:01.500
roeddwn i'n sylweddoli model

00:07:01.500 --> 00:07:03.500
i ddatblygu a datblygu.

00:07:03.500 --> 00:07:05.500
Felly'r syniad hwn,

00:07:35.500 --> 00:07:37.500
roeddwn i'n mynd i weld a allwn i ddatblygu LLM

00:07:37.500 --> 00:07:39.500
i ddysgu i mi sut i'w wneud yn fy hun,

00:07:39.500 --> 00:07:41.500
sy'n mynd i'r cwestiwn cyntaf.

00:07:41.500 --> 00:07:43.500
Pa rôl

00:07:43.500 --> 00:07:45.500
y byddai'r LLM yn ei chwarae?

00:07:45.500 --> 00:07:47.500
Felly, ar hyn o bryd, dewisais ymgyrchu

00:07:47.500 --> 00:07:49.500
rhai o'r llyfrgell yno

00:07:49.500 --> 00:07:51.500
am ddefnyddio LLM mewn addysg.

00:07:51.500 --> 00:07:53.500
Ac roeddwn i'n darganfod papur

00:07:53.500 --> 00:07:55.500
gan Dr. C. Lynn

00:07:55.500 --> 00:07:57.500
am sut y gall ChatGPT helpu

00:07:57.500 --> 00:07:59.500
fel adolygiad dysgu bywyd.

00:07:59.500 --> 00:08:01.500
Felly, yn y papur hon,

00:08:01.500 --> 00:08:03.500
mae Dr. Lynn yn mynd trwy'r fframwaith hwn

00:08:03.500 --> 00:08:05.500
i ddysgu

00:08:05.500 --> 00:08:07.500
a phethau sy'n benodol

00:08:07.500 --> 00:08:09.500
y gall ChatGPT helpu gyda hyn.

00:08:09.500 --> 00:08:11.500
Felly, mae'r ddau gyntaf yn y fframwaith

00:08:11.500 --> 00:08:13.500
yn sefydlu'r golau dysgu,

00:08:13.500 --> 00:08:15.500
sefydlu a chysylltu'r arian cyhoeddiol

00:08:15.500 --> 00:08:17.500
ac yna ddefnyddio

00:08:17.500 --> 00:08:19.500
a chynhyrchu'r gweithgareddau dysgu.

00:08:19.500 --> 00:08:21.500
Felly, dewisais i roi hyn.

00:08:21.500 --> 00:08:23.500
Felly, i fynd yn ôl

00:08:23.500 --> 00:08:25.500
i'r tasg yna,

00:08:25.500 --> 00:08:27.500
y tasg ymgyrchu bywyd.

00:08:27.500 --> 00:08:29.500
Roedd hi'n teimlo'n tasg strech sy'n perffaith

00:08:29.500 --> 00:08:31.500
i'w defnyddio yma, oherwydd rwy'n cael profiad

00:08:31.500 --> 00:08:33.500
o'r tasg hwn. Rwy'n gweithio gyda'r tasg DT.

00:08:33.500 --> 00:08:35.500
Felly, mae'r tasg DT yn anodd tasg html bywyd.

00:08:35.500 --> 00:08:37.500
Mae'n ymgyrchu

00:08:37.500 --> 00:08:39.500
tablau ac mae ganddo ffeithiol yno

00:08:39.500 --> 00:08:41.500
y byddwch chi'n gallu defnyddio'r tasg

00:08:41.500 --> 00:08:43.500
yn y fframwaith

00:08:43.500 --> 00:08:45.500
a chynhyrchu pethau o hynny.

00:08:45.500 --> 00:08:47.500
Felly, rydw i wedi gweithio ar hyn

00:08:47.500 --> 00:08:49.500
o'r fframwaith allan.

00:08:49.500 --> 00:08:51.500
Ac rwy'n gwybod ychydig am Javascript,

00:08:51.500 --> 00:08:53.500
ond ar hyn o bryd, roeddwn i'n gwybod

00:08:53.500 --> 00:08:55.500
llawer iawn am tasg html bywyd.

00:08:55.500 --> 00:08:57.500
Ac roeddwn i ddim yn cael profiad

00:08:57.500 --> 00:08:59.500
o ddefnyddio reaktiwnau cyffredin yn Javascript.

00:08:59.500 --> 00:09:01.500
Felly, mae'n ymddangos fel tasg html bywyd.

00:09:03.500 --> 00:09:05.500
Felly, dasg 1.

00:09:05.500 --> 00:09:07.500
Sefydliadau dysgu.

00:09:07.500 --> 00:09:09.500
Rwy'n hoffi feddwl am hyn o ran sut y byddwn i wedi'i wneud

00:09:09.500 --> 00:09:11.500
os nad oeddwn i'n cael help LLM gyda hyn.

00:09:11.500 --> 00:09:13.500
Felly, rwy'n meddwl y byddwn i wedi bod yn dweud,

00:09:13.500 --> 00:09:15.500
iawn, mae'n amlwg i ddefnyddio tasg allan,

00:09:15.500 --> 00:09:17.500
iawn, ac yn mynd allan gyda hynny.

00:09:17.500 --> 00:09:19.500
Ond mewn gwirionedd,

00:09:19.500 --> 00:09:20.500
gann about my GPT,

00:09:20.500 --> 00:09:22.500
it asked me a number of questions.

00:09:22.500 --> 00:09:24.500
It asked me exactly what I was trying to achieve,

00:09:24.500 --> 00:09:26.500
how long I wanted to spend in it,

00:09:26.500 --> 00:09:28.500
and what past experience I had.

00:09:28.500 --> 00:09:30.500
And from my answers to the questions,

00:09:30.500 --> 00:09:33.500
it ended up coming with this really clear and concise goal.

00:09:33.500 --> 00:09:35.500
And it broke it down into three practical steps.

00:09:35.500 --> 00:09:38.500
So, capturing the event in Javascript,

00:09:38.500 --> 00:09:40.500
then passing that to Shiny,

00:09:40.500 --> 00:09:42.500
and then testing it in an app.

00:09:42.500 --> 00:09:43.500
Now, could I have done this myself?

00:09:43.500 --> 00:09:44.500
Sure.

00:09:44.500 --> 00:09:45.500
But was I likely to?

00:09:45.500 --> 00:09:47.260
Yeah, probably not.

00:09:47.260 --> 00:09:48.500
So it just left me feeling like

00:09:48.500 --> 00:09:51.500
I really knew exactly what I was trying to achieve here.

00:09:51.500 --> 00:09:53.500
So the second step, then,

00:09:53.500 --> 00:09:55.500
locating and accessing resources.

00:09:55.500 --> 00:09:57.500
So, again, like, doing this on my own,

00:09:57.500 --> 00:09:58.500
I'd probably end up Googling things

00:09:58.500 --> 00:10:00.500
and have, like, 50 browser tabs open

00:10:00.500 --> 00:10:01.500
and end up down a rabbit hole

00:10:01.500 --> 00:10:04.500
of kind of reading about a slightly different component.

00:10:04.500 --> 00:10:06.500
But with ChatGPT help,

00:10:06.500 --> 00:10:08.500
I had a couple of questions.

00:10:08.500 --> 00:10:10.500
So how do I prefer learning?

00:10:10.500 --> 00:10:12.500
I said I prefer learning by doing.

00:10:12.500 --> 00:10:13.500
I like having kind of snippets of code

00:10:13.500 --> 00:10:16.500
that I can run and see what happens and play with.

00:10:16.500 --> 00:10:19.500
And it found me really quickly just two resources

00:10:19.500 --> 00:10:21.500
that were perfect for the task at hand.

00:10:21.500 --> 00:10:23.500
So, firstly, the book Javascript for R,

00:10:23.500 --> 00:10:25.500
which has a free copy available online.

00:10:25.500 --> 00:10:29.500
And secondly, a blog post from 2016 by Dina Tali

00:10:29.500 --> 00:10:32.500
that's all about more or less exactly what I was trying to do.

00:10:32.500 --> 00:10:34.500
So, great.

00:10:34.500 --> 00:10:36.500
And I guess this had stopped me kind of having to switch

00:10:36.500 --> 00:10:39.500
between kind of planning and organizing and coding,

00:10:39.500 --> 00:10:42.500
and I could just focus on reading up and writing some code.

00:10:43.500 --> 00:10:46.500
So then, finally, the third step for this

00:10:46.500 --> 00:10:50.500
was this idea of adopting and executing learning activities.

00:10:50.500 --> 00:10:51.500
So there wasn't much back and forth

00:10:51.500 --> 00:10:53.500
between me and ChatGPT at this point,

00:10:53.500 --> 00:10:54.500
because we kind of talked a lot

00:10:54.500 --> 00:10:56.500
about kind of my past experience and things,

00:10:56.500 --> 00:10:58.500
but it came up with this three-step process

00:10:58.500 --> 00:11:00.500
I was going to follow.

00:11:00.500 --> 00:11:02.500
Firstly, I was going to have a look in the DT package

00:11:02.500 --> 00:11:05.500
and kind of try to reverse-engineer the code in there.

00:11:05.500 --> 00:11:07.500
So seeing if I could find the code

00:11:07.500 --> 00:11:09.500
that actually implemented that row selection

00:11:09.500 --> 00:11:12.500
to learn more about exactly how that worked.

00:11:12.500 --> 00:11:14.500
Secondly, build a minimal working demo,

00:11:14.500 --> 00:11:16.500
so in a tiny little shiny app,

00:11:16.500 --> 00:11:19.500
just showing capturing a user event.

00:11:19.500 --> 00:11:22.500
And then thirdly, add it to the actual package.

00:11:22.500 --> 00:11:26.500
But it wasn't just like this three-step process that was useful.

00:11:26.500 --> 00:11:29.500
Around this, it did things like it gave me time boxes,

00:11:29.500 --> 00:11:33.500
so I didn't end up spending too long on each step.

00:11:33.500 --> 00:11:35.500
It also had useful little bits and pieces,

00:11:35.500 --> 00:11:38.500
so with the bit around reverse-engineering DT,

00:11:38.500 --> 00:11:41.500
it actually gave me a link to the exact place in the package

00:11:41.500 --> 00:11:43.500
that I needed to find the code to read,

00:11:43.500 --> 00:11:44.500
which was really helpful,

00:11:44.500 --> 00:11:46.500
not having to track that down myself.

00:11:46.500 --> 00:11:48.500
And it just feels like a lot of these things

00:11:48.500 --> 00:11:50.500
are all about reducing the level of frustration

00:11:50.500 --> 00:11:51.500
that we can end up having

00:11:51.500 --> 00:11:53.500
when we're trying to figure out a new thing.

00:11:53.500 --> 00:11:55.500
But even better than that,

00:11:55.500 --> 00:11:58.500
it also suggested ways that I could use ChatGPT

00:11:58.500 --> 00:12:00.500
to help me with these.

00:12:00.500 --> 00:12:03.500
So for example, when I was reverse-engineering DT,

00:12:03.500 --> 00:12:06.500
it mentioned, okay, any code you don't understand,

00:12:06.500 --> 00:12:08.500
paste it in, and we'll go through step by step.

00:12:08.500 --> 00:12:11.500
And again, that was super useful.

00:12:11.500 --> 00:12:13.500
When I was building my minimal demo,

00:12:13.500 --> 00:12:15.500
the first time I ran it, it wasn't quite right,

00:12:15.500 --> 00:12:17.500
and just being able to paste it straight in

00:12:17.500 --> 00:12:19.500
and figure out what wasn't working,

00:12:19.500 --> 00:12:21.500
again, just reduced that frustration.

00:12:21.500 --> 00:12:24.500
And then when I added the event tracking to the app,

00:12:24.500 --> 00:12:27.500
we ended up in a situation where it wasn't working,

00:12:27.500 --> 00:12:29.500
and I was asking why,

00:12:29.500 --> 00:12:30.500
and the LLM actually asked me,

00:12:30.500 --> 00:12:33.500
well, what do you think you should need to click on

00:12:33.500 --> 00:12:34.500
in this situation?

00:12:34.500 --> 00:12:36.500
And it really felt like a really great

00:12:36.500 --> 00:12:40.500
just learning activity and being tutored on something.

00:12:40.500 --> 00:12:44.500
And so I deem this definitely a success.

00:12:44.500 --> 00:12:46.500
There's a write-up on my blog as well

00:12:46.500 --> 00:12:48.500
with more detail if you're interested.

00:12:48.500 --> 00:12:50.500
And I feel like, for me,

00:12:50.500 --> 00:12:52.500
it was just a really enjoyable learning experience

00:12:52.500 --> 00:12:55.500
because I feel like I'd done the work myself.

00:12:55.500 --> 00:12:57.500
It wasn't the LLM doing the work for me.

00:12:57.500 --> 00:12:59.500
It was scaffolding my learning

00:12:59.500 --> 00:13:01.500
and pointing me in the right direction

00:13:01.500 --> 00:13:03.500
and figuring out what questions I needed to be asking

00:13:03.500 --> 00:13:05.500
and what the right answers were,

00:13:05.500 --> 00:13:06.500
but just not taking over.

00:13:06.500 --> 00:13:11.500
And I genuinely felt quite empowered as a learner.

00:13:11.500 --> 00:13:13.500
So equipped with these ideas

00:13:13.500 --> 00:13:16.500
of the kind of stretch zone projects

00:13:16.500 --> 00:13:18.500
and using the LLM as a tutor,

00:13:18.500 --> 00:13:20.500
I decided to take these ideas

00:13:20.500 --> 00:13:23.500
and apply them to a completely different project.

00:13:23.500 --> 00:13:26.500
And this brings me to my third and final question.

00:13:26.500 --> 00:13:29.500
When is a human the better choice?

00:13:29.500 --> 00:13:32.500
So I'm one of the maintainers of the arrr package,

00:13:32.500 --> 00:13:34.500
and I decided I wanted to have a go

00:13:34.500 --> 00:13:39.500
at contributing to Pyarrow, the Python arrow implementation.

00:13:39.500 --> 00:13:42.500
I decided to work on a task related to magic methods.

00:13:42.500 --> 00:13:43.500
Now, if you don't know what they are,

00:13:43.500 --> 00:13:45.500
it doesn't matter too much for this,

00:13:45.500 --> 00:13:48.500
but it felt like the perfect stretch zone task

00:13:48.500 --> 00:13:51.500
in that I've got experience of the arrr package,

00:13:51.500 --> 00:13:53.500
I can write some Python,

00:13:53.500 --> 00:13:55.500
but I didn't know much about Pyarrow

00:13:55.500 --> 00:13:58.500
and very little about the internals of Python libraries in general.

00:13:58.500 --> 00:14:00.500
So it kind of felt in the right place.

00:14:00.500 --> 00:14:05.500
So next, I needed to figure out what role I wanted the LLM to play.

00:14:05.500 --> 00:14:08.500
So I decided that I was going to write most of the code.

00:14:08.500 --> 00:14:11.500
In this case, you know, this task for me was about learning.

00:14:11.500 --> 00:14:13.500
So I needed to do that myself, really.

00:14:13.500 --> 00:14:15.500
I also wanted to write the test,

00:14:15.500 --> 00:14:16.500
just so I could be really clear

00:14:16.500 --> 00:14:19.500
about what the intentions of the code that I was writing.

00:14:19.500 --> 00:14:23.500
And I was going to get the LLM to help me with any code tweaks.

00:14:23.500 --> 00:14:25.500
Maybe there's bits of how things are done in Python

00:14:25.500 --> 00:14:28.500
that I don't really kind of get with package internals.

00:14:28.500 --> 00:14:31.500
So I was going to use it to help me understand errors

00:14:31.500 --> 00:14:33.500
and to explain any new concepts, like magic methods,

00:14:33.500 --> 00:14:36.500
which I had no idea what they were at the time.

00:14:36.500 --> 00:14:40.500
But also, I had some other help from my friend, Elenka,

00:14:40.500 --> 00:14:42.500
who is a Pyarrow maintainer,

00:14:42.500 --> 00:14:45.500
and she was just going to jump in anywhere I got stuck.

00:14:45.500 --> 00:14:47.500
Okay, so how did it go?

00:14:47.500 --> 00:14:50.500
Well, actually, I feel like this is almost like a kind of fight

00:14:50.500 --> 00:14:52.500
between LLMs and human knowledge,

00:14:52.500 --> 00:14:56.500
almost like a kind of retro video game with different levels.

00:14:56.500 --> 00:14:58.500
So the first level, then, rubber duck.

00:14:58.500 --> 00:15:00.500
So I think probably a lot of people in this room

00:15:00.500 --> 00:15:03.500
have experience of that kind of rubber duck debugging thing,

00:15:03.500 --> 00:15:05.500
where, you know, you've got a problem with some code,

00:15:05.500 --> 00:15:07.500
and in explaining it to an inanimate object,

00:15:07.500 --> 00:15:10.500
you actually find yourself getting closer to the solution

00:15:10.500 --> 00:15:11.500
than you were in the first place,

00:15:11.500 --> 00:15:13.500
without even getting an answer back.

00:15:13.500 --> 00:15:15.500
And I found here, actually,

00:15:15.500 --> 00:15:19.500
when I was trying to create the prompt to kind of put into the LLM,

00:15:19.500 --> 00:15:21.500
half the time, trying to get something specific enough

00:15:21.500 --> 00:15:23.500
that it wasn't going to come back with nonsense

00:15:23.500 --> 00:15:25.500
actually helped me figure out a lot of the problem myself,

00:15:25.500 --> 00:15:28.500
which was great.

00:15:28.500 --> 00:15:31.500
The second level, the LLM as an assistant.

00:15:31.500 --> 00:15:33.500
So there were points at which I was trying to build PyArrow,

00:15:33.500 --> 00:15:35.500
and it's got C++ under it,

00:15:35.500 --> 00:15:37.500
and I'm not super experienced in C++,

00:15:37.500 --> 00:15:39.500
and I ended up with various errors in the build logs,

00:15:39.500 --> 00:15:41.500
and instead of having to troll through

00:15:41.500 --> 00:15:44.500
and figure out what was the problem and what was happening,

00:15:44.500 --> 00:15:50.500
having an LLM just help me pinpoint it really quickly was fantastic.

00:15:50.500 --> 00:15:53.500
So the third level, the LLM as a tutor.

00:15:53.500 --> 00:15:55.500
So as I mentioned, I had no idea

00:15:55.500 --> 00:15:57.500
what magic methods were before this,

00:15:57.500 --> 00:15:59.500
so I got it to come up with a very quick

00:15:59.500 --> 00:16:01.500
sort of mini-tutorial-type thing,

00:16:01.500 --> 00:16:04.500
give me a really quick, simple example of exactly what it was,

00:16:04.500 --> 00:16:07.500
and it just made me feel way more prepared

00:16:07.500 --> 00:16:09.500
for the task I was trying to complete.

00:16:09.500 --> 00:16:12.500
But actually, there was a point at which LLM help

00:16:12.500 --> 00:16:15.500
didn't really take me any further.

00:16:15.500 --> 00:16:19.500
So there was a bit where there were two different conventions

00:16:19.500 --> 00:16:22.500
of how to approach magic methods in Python,

00:16:22.500 --> 00:16:24.500
and there was just conflicting information there.

00:16:24.500 --> 00:16:26.500
I could have asked an LLM,

00:16:26.500 --> 00:16:29.500
but it felt like actually, with that context

00:16:29.500 --> 00:16:32.500
and the context of PyArrow, this needed human intervention.

00:16:32.500 --> 00:16:34.500
So I spoke to Alenka, who helped me

00:16:34.500 --> 00:16:37.500
by just explaining things from her past experience

00:16:37.500 --> 00:16:39.500
and her knowledge of this, and yeah,

00:16:39.500 --> 00:16:42.500
I feel like having somebody acting as a mentor on a project

00:16:42.500 --> 00:16:45.500
is just so important in so many cases.

00:16:45.500 --> 00:16:48.500
But actually, kind of like beyond this,

00:16:48.500 --> 00:16:50.500
I got the pull request done, I got it finished,

00:16:50.500 --> 00:16:52.500
but I wanted to figure out where would be

00:16:52.500 --> 00:16:54.500
another place I could contribute,

00:16:54.500 --> 00:16:56.500
what were other tickets I could take on

00:16:56.500 --> 00:16:58.500
that would be kind of fun, interesting,

00:16:58.500 --> 00:17:00.500
and a good learning experience.

00:17:00.500 --> 00:17:02.500
And I mentioned it to a few other people

00:17:02.500 --> 00:17:04.500
collaborating on the project,

00:17:04.500 --> 00:17:06.500
and they started actually tagging me on issues.

00:17:06.500 --> 00:17:08.500
And again, I think this thing of having somebody

00:17:08.500 --> 00:17:10.500
acting as a sponsor, helping kind of figure out opportunities

00:17:10.500 --> 00:17:13.500
to kind of push you further, again, so, so important

00:17:13.500 --> 00:17:16.500
to have that human kind of side of things there.

00:17:16.500 --> 00:17:18.500
So actually, it's kind of not about

00:17:18.500 --> 00:17:20.500
sort of LLM versus human knowledge,

00:17:20.500 --> 00:17:24.500
it's more about just where to kind of rely on each.

00:17:24.500 --> 00:17:27.500
And so to kind of go back to the overall kind of question

00:17:27.500 --> 00:17:30.500
of how can I be more productive using LLMs,

00:17:30.500 --> 00:17:33.500
I think it's important to keep in mind

00:17:33.500 --> 00:17:36.500
that I feel like LLMs shine in the stretch zone,

00:17:36.500 --> 00:17:38.500
so like projects that can just take you a bit further

00:17:38.500 --> 00:17:41.500
than where you are at the moment.

00:17:41.500 --> 00:17:43.500
Not all the time, but sometimes,

00:17:43.500 --> 00:17:46.500
actually using LLMs to scaffold the work

00:17:46.500 --> 00:17:50.500
and not doing it for you can be really valuable.

00:17:50.500 --> 00:17:52.500
And finally, like not forgetting the importance

00:17:52.500 --> 00:17:54.500
of human connection, like really thinking about

00:17:54.500 --> 00:17:57.500
when to rely on people instead.

00:17:57.500 --> 00:17:59.500
And I think by doing all of these things,

00:17:59.500 --> 00:18:01.500
we can kind of shift from passive use of tools

00:18:01.500 --> 00:18:03.500
to like really active learning,

00:18:03.500 --> 00:18:05.500
and that can help to build long-term skills

00:18:05.500 --> 00:18:07.500
and productivity.

00:18:07.500 --> 00:18:09.500
Thank you.

00:18:09.500 --> 00:18:11.500
Thank you.

00:18:14.500 --> 00:18:16.500
Thank you so much, Nick.

00:18:16.500 --> 00:18:18.500
We did have one question.

00:18:18.500 --> 00:18:20.500
Did you make the art for your slides

00:18:20.500 --> 00:18:22.500
because they're so awesome?

00:18:22.500 --> 00:18:24.500
Yeah, I got obsessed with Canva the other day.

00:18:24.500 --> 00:18:25.500
Oh, no, the other ones.

00:18:25.500 --> 00:18:26.500
Do you know what?

00:18:26.500 --> 00:18:29.500
I saw Hadley's talk at USAR where he'd done a lot of that

00:18:29.500 --> 00:18:32.500
and was like, well, that's a good idea to pay homage to.

00:18:32.500 --> 00:18:34.500
So, yeah.

00:18:34.500 --> 00:18:35.500
Cool.

00:18:35.500 --> 00:18:37.500
Yeah, thank you so much.

00:18:37.500 --> 00:18:38.500
Thank you.

00:18:38.500 --> 00:18:39.500
Thank you.

00:18:39.500 --> 00:18:40.500
Thank you.

00:18:40.500 --> 00:18:42.500
Thank you.

00:18:42.500 --> 00:18:43.500
Sorry.

